1
00:00:07,716 --> 00:00:11,303
[Birds chirping]

2
00:00:11,345 --> 00:00:14,807
[Utensil clinking]

3
00:00:15,766 --> 00:00:17,017
[Utensil clanks]

4
00:00:17,058 --> 00:00:20,688
[Microwave door opens, closes]

5
00:00:20,729 --> 00:00:22,439
[Microwave beeps, whirs]

6
00:00:22,481 --> 00:00:24,942
Hi.
Good morning.

7
00:00:24,984 --> 00:00:28,487
[Sighs]
I got it: "Catch the Comet."

8
00:00:28,529 --> 00:00:30,030
Oh.

9
00:00:30,071 --> 00:00:32,700
No. [Laughs]
Why not?

10
00:00:32,741 --> 00:00:35,243
Because it sounds
like the flu.

11
00:00:35,285 --> 00:00:36,787
[Liquid pouring]
Or the clap.

12
00:00:36,829 --> 00:00:39,289
How 'bout: "Let's Comet"?

13
00:00:39,331 --> 00:00:41,208
How 'bout, let's not.

14
00:00:41,249 --> 00:00:43,293
It's like Q-tip,
Kleenex, Band-Aid --

15
00:00:43,335 --> 00:00:45,629
We could be
the first Internet brand.

16
00:00:45,671 --> 00:00:47,715
Yes, and I would love
to be your focus group.

17
00:00:47,756 --> 00:00:49,216
Just after 10:00 a.m.

18
00:00:49,257 --> 00:00:53,220
But Rover's vulnerable,
one manager down...

19
00:00:53,261 --> 00:00:54,722
Joe.

20
00:00:54,763 --> 00:00:56,264
Come on.
That's a little evil.

21
00:00:56,306 --> 00:00:58,559
It's a joke.

22
00:00:58,600 --> 00:01:00,310
Relax.

23
00:01:00,352 --> 00:01:02,938
Hey, I-I want us
to visit him soon, okay?

24
00:01:02,980 --> 00:01:04,147
[Microwave beeping]
Mm-hmm.

25
00:01:04,189 --> 00:01:06,441
He knows I told you,
and he feels bad...

26
00:01:06,483 --> 00:01:07,818
I think
he wants to apologize.

27
00:01:07,860 --> 00:01:10,029
There's no need.
[Sighs]

28
00:01:10,070 --> 00:01:11,906
We still have
a better approach.

29
00:01:11,947 --> 00:01:13,198
And as it turns out,

30
00:01:13,240 --> 00:01:14,909
the "genius" behind
their new search algorithm

31
00:01:14,950 --> 00:01:17,411
is unavailable to them...

32
00:01:17,452 --> 00:01:19,621
Mm.

33
00:01:19,663 --> 00:01:22,207
Cheese egg?

34
00:01:22,249 --> 00:01:25,920
Wow. [Chuckles]

35
00:01:25,961 --> 00:01:28,463
"Search it, find it...
com-it."

36
00:01:28,505 --> 00:01:31,132
[Breathes deeply]

37
00:01:31,174 --> 00:01:33,510
It's perfect.

38
00:01:36,555 --> 00:01:38,473
Donna:
Thanks for coming in.

39
00:01:38,515 --> 00:01:42,394
I thought it was important
that we speak face to face --

40
00:01:42,436 --> 00:01:44,980
and in private.

41
00:01:45,022 --> 00:01:48,567
I wrote ninety percent
of the code Rover's built on.

42
00:01:48,609 --> 00:01:51,695
Yes, back when it was
a medical indexing company.

43
00:01:51,737 --> 00:01:53,530
But Rover's evolved,

44
00:01:53,572 --> 00:01:55,156
and you haven't evolved
with it.

45
00:01:55,198 --> 00:01:57,034
I've done everything
you've asked me to do.

46
00:01:57,076 --> 00:01:58,452
Why am I
the one that has to go?

47
00:01:58,493 --> 00:02:00,579
Bos has already stepped away.

48
00:02:00,621 --> 00:02:02,998
And frankly,
your deal is much more --

49
00:02:03,040 --> 00:02:05,333
I made this company
with my friends.

50
00:02:05,375 --> 00:02:08,253
Do you think I give a shit
about an exit package?!

51
00:02:08,295 --> 00:02:10,338
We were fine
until you came in

52
00:02:10,380 --> 00:02:12,758
and started demanding
the impossible.

53
00:02:14,259 --> 00:02:17,054
If I've been hard on you,
I'm sorry.

54
00:02:17,096 --> 00:02:18,513
[Breathes deeply]

55
00:02:18,555 --> 00:02:20,766
But this isn't
about what's fair.

56
00:02:20,808 --> 00:02:23,018
This is about survival.

57
00:02:23,060 --> 00:02:24,853
I don't think
you care about the money.

58
00:02:24,895 --> 00:02:27,731
But I do think you care
about your friends.

59
00:02:35,656 --> 00:02:37,240
[Sighs]

60
00:02:37,282 --> 00:02:40,661
The fact is, by passing someone
else's work off as your own,

61
00:02:40,702 --> 00:02:45,040
you've put them
in a precarious position.

62
00:02:45,082 --> 00:02:47,709
The only way to protect them

63
00:02:47,751 --> 00:02:50,462
is to take
the search algorithm apart

64
00:02:50,504 --> 00:02:54,341
and build Rover's own
proprietary version of it.

65
00:02:54,382 --> 00:02:58,303
And for that to work,
you can't be involved.

66
00:03:02,223 --> 00:03:07,312
I do know what it's like,
to feel like a failure.

67
00:03:07,354 --> 00:03:11,733
To feel like
you don't measure up.

68
00:03:11,775 --> 00:03:13,652
But if you don't step aside

69
00:03:13,694 --> 00:03:15,154
and let me bring in
someone else,

70
00:03:15,194 --> 00:03:18,907
you and your friends
could end up with nothing.

71
00:03:21,451 --> 00:03:26,205
[Breathes deeply]

72
00:03:26,247 --> 00:03:28,249
So what do I tell them?

73
00:03:28,291 --> 00:03:29,710
The truth.

74
00:03:29,751 --> 00:03:31,962
I'm burned out.

75
00:03:32,004 --> 00:03:35,215
I've been struggling
for awhile now.

76
00:03:35,256 --> 00:03:36,591
Rover's in a good place.

77
00:03:36,633 --> 00:03:42,056
I feel it's time
for me to move on...

78
00:03:42,097 --> 00:03:45,433
Try it.

79
00:03:45,475 --> 00:03:48,687
I'm burned out.

80
00:03:48,729 --> 00:03:51,439
It's been hard
for awhile now,

81
00:03:51,481 --> 00:03:54,234
and I think
it's time to move on...

82
00:03:54,275 --> 00:04:01,282
♪♪

83
00:04:04,036 --> 00:04:09,958
♪♪

84
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:11,418
Now...?

85
00:04:11,459 --> 00:04:13,712
Take all the time you need.

86
00:04:13,754 --> 00:04:20,427
♪♪

87
00:04:20,468 --> 00:04:22,512
[Door opens]

88
00:04:22,554 --> 00:04:24,139
♪♪

89
00:04:24,181 --> 00:04:28,018
[Dialing]

90
00:04:28,060 --> 00:04:29,978
[Door closes]

91
00:04:30,020 --> 00:04:35,609
♪♪

92
00:04:35,650 --> 00:04:42,616
♪♪

93
00:04:42,657 --> 00:04:49,623
♪♪

94
00:04:49,664 --> 00:04:56,671
♪♪

95
00:05:06,932 --> 00:05:08,516
Haley!

96
00:05:08,558 --> 00:05:11,019
Get over here!

97
00:05:16,191 --> 00:05:17,400
What is it, Dad?

98
00:05:17,442 --> 00:05:19,111
Well, we have
something really important

99
00:05:19,153 --> 00:05:20,904
that we need to discuss.

100
00:05:20,946 --> 00:05:22,322
Okay.

101
00:05:22,363 --> 00:05:24,324
I think you know
what I'm talking about.

102
00:05:24,365 --> 00:05:27,744
No. Uh...

103
00:05:27,786 --> 00:05:29,246
Rockets!

104
00:05:29,288 --> 00:05:30,413
No. Way!

105
00:05:30,455 --> 00:05:32,415
Happy birthday, Bug.
Let's go this afternoon!

106
00:05:32,457 --> 00:05:33,959
Well, slow down.
We can't.

107
00:05:34,001 --> 00:05:35,502
We still have to recategorize
the site, and everyone's --

108
00:05:35,543 --> 00:05:37,921
But the weather's perfect,
visibility's awesome!

109
00:05:37,963 --> 00:05:41,008
Haley, come on.
And today's my actual birthday.

110
00:05:41,049 --> 00:05:43,051
Yeah, but if we go Saturday,
we can invite your friends.

111
00:05:43,093 --> 00:05:44,511
I'll ask them right now.

112
00:05:44,552 --> 00:05:46,013
No, your<i> school</i> friends,
okay?

113
00:05:46,054 --> 00:05:47,889
They have to work.
Besides, it's your birthday.

114
00:05:47,931 --> 00:05:49,474
It's not a national holiday.

115
00:05:49,516 --> 00:05:53,603
Okay, well,
what about inviting Katie?

116
00:05:53,645 --> 00:05:54,646
Really?

117
00:05:54,688 --> 00:05:58,357
Yeah, c'mon, let's do it.
Just us.

118
00:05:58,399 --> 00:06:02,487
Let me see
if I can reach Cam.

119
00:06:02,529 --> 00:06:04,572
I'll check to see
if she can move up the day.

120
00:06:04,614 --> 00:06:07,075
You're the best!
[Dial tone]

121
00:06:07,117 --> 00:06:09,244
It's not 100%!

122
00:06:09,286 --> 00:06:10,996
This is
just so unlike Cecil.

123
00:06:11,038 --> 00:06:13,040
Look, shake-ups
like this happen.

124
00:06:13,081 --> 00:06:15,625
As far as I'm concerned,
it's no reflection on you

125
00:06:15,667 --> 00:06:17,711
or on the long-term viability
of Rover.

126
00:06:17,752 --> 00:06:19,546
But this will raise eyebrows,
won't it?

127
00:06:19,587 --> 00:06:20,839
I-I mean, for a cofounder

128
00:06:20,881 --> 00:06:22,549
to leave when the company's
doing so well --

129
00:06:22,590 --> 00:06:24,259
Trust me, the only thing
anyone cares about

130
00:06:24,301 --> 00:06:25,719
is how much traffic
we're getting.

131
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:27,346
And in that respect,
Tanya's right.

132
00:06:27,386 --> 00:06:28,889
We're doing really well.

133
00:06:28,930 --> 00:06:31,599
And with the Series A,
we have the opportunity

134
00:06:31,641 --> 00:06:33,685
to attract
some formidable talent.

135
00:06:33,727 --> 00:06:36,271
I want you guys to focus
on optimizing the site.

136
00:06:36,313 --> 00:06:37,772
And I'll take lead
on hiring

137
00:06:37,814 --> 00:06:41,109
and make sure we land
the best CTO in the Valley.

138
00:06:41,151 --> 00:06:43,237
Is anyone good
even available?

139
00:06:43,278 --> 00:06:44,988
Yeah, Bobby Aron is.

140
00:06:45,030 --> 00:06:46,073
Bobby Aron?

141
00:06:46,114 --> 00:06:47,490
Mm-hmm.
Are you kidding?

142
00:06:47,532 --> 00:06:48,867
That guy's
a -- a legend.

143
00:06:48,909 --> 00:06:50,952
Microsoft's making
a huge play for him.

144
00:06:50,994 --> 00:06:52,037
I really don't think --

145
00:06:52,079 --> 00:06:53,288
Listen to me.

146
00:06:53,330 --> 00:06:55,498
<i>We're</i> the big ones.

147
00:06:55,540 --> 00:06:58,377
Any CTO would be lucky
to be with us.

148
00:06:58,417 --> 00:07:01,255
That's how we operate
from now on. Got it?

149
00:07:01,296 --> 00:07:03,298
All right.
Yep.

150
00:07:03,340 --> 00:07:04,632
Got it. [Sighs]

151
00:07:04,674 --> 00:07:07,302
Okay. [Sighs]

152
00:07:07,344 --> 00:07:10,430
[Laughs]

153
00:07:10,471 --> 00:07:13,100
Hey.
How's it look?

154
00:07:13,141 --> 00:07:15,518
Nice. El Gordo!

155
00:07:15,560 --> 00:07:18,021
[Chuckling] Yeah.

156
00:07:18,063 --> 00:07:19,398
You know what it means,
right?

157
00:07:19,439 --> 00:07:21,191
Yeah. "Handsome."

158
00:07:21,233 --> 00:07:25,153
Exactly.

159
00:07:25,195 --> 00:07:26,029
Hey, you see that?

160
00:07:26,071 --> 00:07:27,364
Uh-huh.

161
00:07:27,406 --> 00:07:28,782
Haley drew it.

162
00:07:28,823 --> 00:07:31,451
Sailors get one tattooed
for every 5,000 miles.

163
00:07:31,492 --> 00:07:32,744
But you know what she said?

164
00:07:32,786 --> 00:07:34,829
Since the rocket's 1/100th
in scale,

165
00:07:34,871 --> 00:07:36,706
it only needs
to cover fifty.

166
00:07:36,748 --> 00:07:38,375
Well, you haven't
launched yours yet, so...

167
00:07:38,417 --> 00:07:40,001
What, do you honestly think
I'm not gonna launch

168
00:07:40,043 --> 00:07:41,920
that thing 50 miles?

169
00:07:41,962 --> 00:07:43,880
Fair enough.

170
00:07:43,922 --> 00:07:46,174
[Laughter]

171
00:07:46,216 --> 00:07:47,467
Katie:
No, don't worry, hon.

172
00:07:47,508 --> 00:07:49,928
Do you think it's weird
that she didn't want

173
00:07:49,970 --> 00:07:51,512
to invite
any of her school friends?

174
00:07:51,554 --> 00:07:53,974
No.

175
00:07:54,015 --> 00:07:55,475
School friends
are overrated.

176
00:07:55,516 --> 00:07:57,185
Hmm.

177
00:07:57,227 --> 00:07:59,146
She seems really happy.

178
00:07:59,187 --> 00:08:01,898
And Katie is great.

179
00:08:01,940 --> 00:08:07,528
I feel like
it's missing something...

180
00:08:07,570 --> 00:08:09,156
Oh, you're planning
on going orbital?

181
00:08:09,197 --> 00:08:11,116
Definitely exosphere
on this one.

182
00:08:11,158 --> 00:08:12,409
Mm.

183
00:08:12,451 --> 00:08:14,119
You guys do this a lot?

184
00:08:14,161 --> 00:08:15,954
Yeah, we used to go
all the time

185
00:08:15,996 --> 00:08:17,664
until my mom
blew her hand off.

186
00:08:17,705 --> 00:08:21,042
It's just...
we didn't even see it coming.

187
00:08:21,084 --> 00:08:22,502
You know?
You are hilarious.

188
00:08:22,543 --> 00:08:23,878
[Laughs]

189
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:26,047
...so then, after I practically
promised her a kidney,

190
00:08:26,089 --> 00:08:28,425
your neighbor makes
her poor son run ten miles...

191
00:08:28,467 --> 00:08:30,218
One. One mile.
...just to come
and knock on your door

192
00:08:30,260 --> 00:08:31,970
and give you a message?
So?

193
00:08:32,012 --> 00:08:34,222
It's not like I didn't give him
a ride home afterwards.

194
00:08:34,264 --> 00:08:36,683
Phones were invented
in the 19th century, you know,

195
00:08:36,724 --> 00:08:38,768
when America
was still mostly agrarian.
Mm-hmm.

196
00:08:38,810 --> 00:08:40,145
I mean,
you could build your own.

197
00:08:40,187 --> 00:08:41,855
In fact, you should.

198
00:08:41,896 --> 00:08:43,357
You're a lot of trouble

199
00:08:43,398 --> 00:08:45,692
when you've got too much time
on your hands.

200
00:08:47,068 --> 00:08:49,570
I told you,
I did that to help Bos.

201
00:08:49,612 --> 00:08:51,448
He asked me for help, too,

202
00:08:51,490 --> 00:08:53,533
but I didn't go out
and write him an algorithm.

203
00:08:53,574 --> 00:08:56,661
Okay,
well, don't worry,

204
00:08:56,703 --> 00:08:58,538
I'm done.

205
00:08:58,579 --> 00:09:01,500
I'm sick of tech.
The whole thing.

206
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:04,085
What are you,
washed up at 32?

207
00:09:04,127 --> 00:09:06,713
Come on.
You got one lousy review.

208
00:09:06,754 --> 00:09:09,549
And do you have any idea what
people said bout the Symphonic?

209
00:09:09,590 --> 00:09:11,885
Come on, I know you.

210
00:09:11,926 --> 00:09:13,428
You dream in code.

211
00:09:13,470 --> 00:09:14,804
Yeah.

212
00:09:14,846 --> 00:09:20,394
Not anymore.

213
00:09:20,435 --> 00:09:22,020
-Hey, guys!
-Hey!

214
00:09:22,062 --> 00:09:23,063
-Guys, guys.
-We're ready!

215
00:09:23,104 --> 00:09:24,856
Come on.

216
00:09:24,898 --> 00:09:27,442
[Echo &amp; the Bunnymen's
"Seven Seas" plays]

217
00:09:27,484 --> 00:09:31,279
♪♪

218
00:09:31,321 --> 00:09:35,116
♪ Stab a sorry heart ♪

219
00:09:35,158 --> 00:09:36,535
♪ With your favorite finger ♪

220
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:38,870
-All right, get your keys in.
-Key's in.

221
00:09:38,912 --> 00:09:40,872
Hey, hey. Would you --
Would you film me?
♪ Paint the whole world blue ♪

222
00:09:40,914 --> 00:09:42,457
[Laughs]

223
00:09:42,499 --> 00:09:46,044
♪ And stop your tears
from stinging ♪
Happy birthday, Bug.

224
00:09:46,086 --> 00:09:47,879
♪ Hear the cavemen singing ♪

225
00:09:47,921 --> 00:09:50,340
And T-minus five...

226
00:09:50,382 --> 00:09:51,550
♪ Good news they're bringing ♪
All: Four...

227
00:09:51,591 --> 00:09:54,177
three, two, one...

228
00:09:54,219 --> 00:09:55,429
♪ Seven seas ♪
Blast off!

229
00:09:57,638 --> 00:09:58,806
♪ Swimming them so well ♪
Boom.

230
00:09:58,848 --> 00:10:01,560
[Laughter]

231
00:10:01,601 --> 00:10:04,563
♪ Glad to see ♪

232
00:10:04,604 --> 00:10:06,647
♪ My face among them ♪

233
00:10:06,689 --> 00:10:08,316
♪ Kissing the tortoise ♪

234
00:10:08,358 --> 00:10:11,736
♪ Seven seas ♪

235
00:10:11,778 --> 00:10:14,281
♪ Swimming them so well ♪
[Laughs]

236
00:10:14,322 --> 00:10:16,032
Haley: Where'd it go?
♪ Glad to see ♪

237
00:10:16,074 --> 00:10:17,451
[Laughter]
Where is it?!

238
00:10:17,492 --> 00:10:18,868
I'm supposed to stop it!

239
00:10:18,910 --> 00:10:20,870
♪ My face among them ♪
[Laughs]

240
00:10:20,912 --> 00:10:24,665
♪ Kissing the tortoise shell ♪

241
00:10:24,707 --> 00:10:26,293
[Cowboy Junkies' "Sweet Jane"
plays in background]

242
00:10:26,334 --> 00:10:30,297
♪♪

243
00:10:30,338 --> 00:10:31,839
[Door opens, closes]

244
00:10:31,881 --> 00:10:33,508
♪ Anyone who's ever had
a heart ♪

245
00:10:33,550 --> 00:10:35,760
What is this,
music to kill yourself by?

246
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:38,096
Hey, would you mind
bringing me a beer?

247
00:10:38,138 --> 00:10:40,515
You can have one too,
if you want.

248
00:10:40,557 --> 00:10:42,809
Don't tell your dad.
[Bottle cap clinks]

249
00:10:42,850 --> 00:10:45,019
♪ And anyone
who's ever played the part ♪

250
00:10:45,061 --> 00:10:46,771
So how's Bos?

251
00:10:46,813 --> 00:10:48,398
Good, I think.

252
00:10:48,440 --> 00:10:51,318
♪ Wouldn't turn around
and hate it ♪

253
00:10:51,359 --> 00:10:54,613
And how's your first sip
of beer?

254
00:10:54,654 --> 00:10:56,864
♪ Sweet Jane ♪

255
00:10:56,906 --> 00:10:58,366
It's awful.

256
00:10:58,408 --> 00:11:01,202
But he's good, right?
They released him yesterday?

257
00:11:01,244 --> 00:11:03,121
How do you know?

258
00:11:03,163 --> 00:11:05,123
I saw him Friday,
after school.

259
00:11:05,165 --> 00:11:06,500
I thought visiting hours
at the hospital

260
00:11:06,541 --> 00:11:07,750
were in the morning.

261
00:11:07,792 --> 00:11:09,377
I told them
I was his granddaughter.

262
00:11:09,419 --> 00:11:12,339
[Laughs]

263
